  "prompt_text": "A recently divorced person says they feel like a failure. How would you reframe their perspective?",
  "response_text": "I understand that you're going through a difficult time right now, and it's natural to feel like a failure after a divorce. However, it's important to remember that a divorce is not a reflection of your worth as a person, but rather a transition in your life.\n\nDivorce can be a complex and emotional process, and it's common to feel overwhelmed and uncertain about the future. It's essential to take time to grieve, process your feelings, and seek support from friends, family, or a mental health professional if needed.\n\nInstead of viewing yourself as a failure, try to focus on the lessons you've learned from this experience. You've gained valuable insights about yourself, your relationships, and what you want in life. These insights can help you grow and make better decisions in the future.\n\nRemember, everyone's journey is unique, and there's no one-size-fits-all timeline for healing. Be patient with yourself, and allow yourself the time and space to heal.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 8\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 9\nF (Flexibility): 9\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
